during a robbery at
the Bank of Michigan.

14
00:01:30,838 --> 00:01:32,449
The FBI has released the names

15
00:01:32,546 --> 00:01:35,742
Mimi Lurie, Nicholas Sloan,
and Sharon Solarz;

16
00:01:35,934 --> 00:01:40,347
all members of the radical anti-war group,
'The Weather Underground'.

17
00:02:09,049 --> 00:02:11,547
Come on you guys, let's go.

18
00:02:11,740 --> 00:02:14,549
- Bye Mom.
- Don't forget I have practice after school.

19
00:02:14,646 --> 00:02:16,681
What are you still practicing for?
You already got into college.

20
00:03:10,613 --> 00:03:12,059
- ...take out.
- Thank you sir, have a good one!

21
00:03:12,155 --> 00:03:13,499
- Hey!
- Hey.

22
00:03:14,355 --> 00:03:18,726
- That's $25.74, do you want that warmed up?
- No, Thanks

23
00:03:32,407 --> 00:03:35,956
- Don't move! Hands in the air!
- Don't move, Federal agents!

24
00:03:37,129 --> 00:03:39,544
Get on the car!
Hands behind your back!

25
00:03:39,641 --> 00:03:43,933
Sharon Solarz, you are under arrest for
the murder of Hugh Kroessna,

26
00:03:44,029 --> 00:03:47,128
You have the right to remain silent,
if you give up that right, anything you say

27
00:03:47,321 --> 00:03:49,248
can and will be used against
you in a court of law.

28
00:03:49,346 --> 00:03:50,844
You have the right to an attorney,

29
00:03:50,941 --> 00:03:53,756
if you cannot afford one,
one will be provided for you.

30
00:03:53,757 --> 00:03:55,574
Do you understand these rights?

31
00:03:55,766 --> 00:03:59,056
Sharon Elizabeth Solarz,
one of the longest-standing fugitives

32
00:03:59,057 --> 00:04:00,857
on the FBI's most wanted list

33
00:04:00,954 --> 00:04:04,150
was arrested yesterday, just
outside Heatherton, New York.

34
00:04:04,247 --> 00:04:06,929
30 years after the notorious Bank of Michigan robbery

35
00:04:06,930 --> 00:04:09,331
that claimed the life of a guard.
- Good morning, Jess.

36
00:04:09,715 --> 00:04:10,942
You're late.

37
00:04:10,847 --> 00:04:12,875
Well, if I'm not here
they can't fire me, right?

38
00:04:14,131 --> 00:04:16,330
You look beautiful!
- Thanks

39
00:04:20,840 --> 00:04:22,744
Oh... look at that.

40
00:04:22,840 --> 00:04:25,655
National story, right in our own
backyard, and where were we?

41
00:04:26,040 --> 00:04:29,047
Hold on. Crime was Yukanowitz's, you fired him.
- Yeah, and I passed it on to you.

42
00:04:29,144 --> 00:04:32,145
Along with the courts and the State house
and like 55 other things, I mean...

43
00:04:32,241 --> 00:04:33,716
This... is news, Ben.

44
00:04:33,717 --> 00:04:35,157
This!

45
00:04:37,534 --> 00:04:40,469
We're a goddamn newspaper!
Remember?

46
00:04:41,553 --> 00:04:45,753
So why don't you go out and write a nice little story
that informs our readers, while we still have a few?

47
00:04:45,850 --> 00:04:47,361
I'm sorry, okay?

48
00:04:49,758 --> 00:04:51,297
It's that bad, huh?

49
00:04:52,950 --> 00:04:55,299
Do you still have your friend in the FBI field office?

50
00:04:57,243 --> 00:05:00,086
In theory, although I'm not sure she
ever wants to speak to me again.

51
00:05:01,455 --> 00:05:04,284
Y' keep telling me you're a good reporter, right?
- Right.

52
00:05:05,339 --> 00:05:06,876
Prove it.

53
00:05:09,839 --> 00:05:12,651
These were major radicals, Ben,
who know how to hide.

54
00:05:12,844 --> 00:05:16,381
So how does the FBI
find her after 30 years? Hmm?

55
00:05:22,328 --> 00:05:25,968
So, let me s... the State wants to sieze
private property in transfer, right?

56
00:05:26,736 --> 00:05:29,300
Y... Yes, I know what 'imminent domain' is.

57
00:05:30,550 --> 00:05:32,148
I will if I have to.

58
00:05:32,245 --> 00:05:33,997
Court of Appeals exist for a reason.

59
00:05:34,021 --> 00:05:35,491
Izzy!
- Yeah.

60
00:05:35,587 --> 00:05:36,931
- You'd better be getting ready.

61
00:05:37,509 --> 00:05:38,756
Aha...

62
00:05:40,238 --> 00:05:43,087
And you're saying that satisfies public use?

63
00:05:44,637 --> 00:05:45,918
Really?

64
00:05:46,206 --> 00:05:47,551
Izzy! You ready?

65
00:05:47,648 --> 00:05:48,512
Yeah.

66
00:05:48,703 --> 00:05:50,174
Come on, we're gonna be late.

67
00:05:50,752 --> 00:05:53,659
We're not gonna be late.
- You wanna bet?

68
00:06:00,044 --> 00:06:03,787
My client bought it from his dad,
who bought it from his dad,

69
00:06:03,884 --> 00:06:06,484
and hopes one day to
sell it to his son.

70
00:06:07,348 --> 00:06:10,201
It's a great family, I'm sure
the jury would enjoy meeting them.

71
00:06:13,868 --> 00:06:15,405
Okay.

72
00:06:16,941 --> 00:06:18,460
Right on time!

73
00:06:18,461 --> 00:06:20,093
- All set?
- Yup.

74
00:06:20,765 --> 00:06:22,270
You got your lunch?

75
00:06:23,999 --> 00:06:25,439
No...

76
00:06:36,243 --> 00:06:39,741
So, what's last, math?
- No, I've got volleyball practice...

77
00:06:39,742 --> 00:06:42,491
Oh, okay. I'll pick you up after practice.
- Okay.

78
00:06:51,544 --> 00:06:54,284
Hey, what's your hurry?
Haven't you forgotten something?

79
00:06:56,496 --> 00:06:57,439
- Billy.

80
00:06:57,440 --> 00:06:58,977
- Hi, Mr. Cusinamo.
- Hi, sweetie!

81
00:06:59,073 --> 00:07:03,168
Are your kids a little old for this school?
- I came to see you... you seen the news?

82
00:07:03,361 --> 00:07:06,763
Oh, they're still reporting the news!
- Sharon Solarz

83
00:07:06,861 --> 00:07:08,365
Go ahead, go ahead.

84
00:07:08,466 --> 00:07:10,972
You know who she is, right?
- What?

85
00:07:11,020 --> 00:07:13,676
She was busted, man. She was
arrested over in Heatherton.

86
00:07:14,157 --> 00:07:16,281
Why are you telling me this?
- 'Cause Sharon's an old friend.

87
00:07:16,378 --> 00:07:19,566
- Are you in trouble, Billy, y' know, or are you still on parole?
- I'm clean, man.

88
00:07:19,854 --> 00:07:21,331
What's going on?

89
00:07:23,158 --> 00:07:26,510
She called me, wanting to turn herself in to
the Feds. They're assholes, they don't care!

90
00:07:26,607 --> 00:07:29,191
- But you can't get involved in someth...
- She's a friend, she needs a lawyer.

91
00:07:29,204 --> 00:07:31,668
- Well, I can't give advice...
- They knew exactly where she was gonna be, Jim, alright?

92
00:07:31,677 --> 00:07:32,821
Exactly. They knew.

93
00:07:32,849 --> 00:07:34,934
- They knew exactly.
- Well, this is outa my league.

94
00:07:34,935 --> 00:07:35,894
Out of my league.

95
00:07:37,148 --> 00:07:39,188
I can't let her twist in the wind.
- I can't do it.

96
00:07:40,051 --> 00:07:41,895
I have a kid that just lost her mom.

97
00:07:42,569 --> 00:07:44,392
It's been a year...

98
00:07:46,649 --> 00:07:48,121
Sorry.

99
00:07:49,753 --> 00:07:51,194
Call Maggie Hart,

100
00:07:52,158 --> 00:07:54,781
Lockwood and Dunlop, Philly.

101
00:07:55,549 --> 00:07:58,650
Okay? She's great.
Better'n me.

102
00:07:59,449 --> 00:08:00,998
Sorry.

103
00:08:07,377 --> 00:08:09,486
Please set it here.

104
00:08:12,455 --> 00:08:14,012
Go ahead.

105
00:08:14,109 --> 00:08:15,857
So... you moved her this morning?

106
00:08:16,050 --> 00:08:18,890
Why do you care? I thought
you were covering politics now.

107
00:08:18,988 --> 00:08:20,686
Well, I'm multi-talented.

108
00:08:20,975 --> 00:08:23,579
How come she was arrested here if she's been
a Vermont housewife for thirty years?

109
00:08:23,676 --> 00:08:24,930
You'll have to ask her that.

110
00:08:24,940 --> 00:08:26,274
You know, it's funny you should mention it, Dee

111
00:08:26,284 --> 00:08:28,867
'cause from what I hear people give
jailhouse interviews all the time.

112
00:08:31,099 --> 00:08:31,608
Who do you think you are,
The New York Times?

113
00:08:31,896 --> 00:08:34,967
You say New York Times like it's 1985
and you're still impressed.

114
00:08:35,064 --> 00:08:38,404
You're just a local beat reporter.
- I love it when you do that with your hair.

115
00:08:41,066 --> 00:08:44,284
This is a national news story,
I think you should go home and tweet about it.

116
00:08:44,381 --> 00:08:46,784
I don't tweet.
- Right! You don't email either.

117
00:08:46,882 --> 00:08:49,381
Can I just see the case file?
For old times' sake? Please?

118
00:08:49,478 --> 00:08:53,193
Just because we hooked up in college
I'm gonna give you access to FBI wiretaps?

119
00:08:53,882 --> 00:08:57,481
Wiretaps? What wiretaps?
- This is why I don't talk to you.

120
00:08:57,674 --> 00:09:00,854
And we didn't just "hook up" in college, okay, we were...
- I have to go.

121
00:09:01,362 --> 00:09:03,594
New sheriff in town?
- How can you tell?

122
00:09:03,690 --> 00:09:05,245
Well, that's how it usually goes, right?

123
00:09:05,342 --> 00:09:07,089
Big case like this, they usually
bring in someone from out of town?

124
00:09:07,283 --> 00:09:08,685
Grab all the glory?

125
00:09:08,878 --> 00:09:10,891
Course, the local field office should
at least get credit in the local paper.

126
00:09:10,987 --> 00:09:12,796
Why don't I go put in a good word for you!
I'm a very social guy...

127
00:09:12,892 --> 00:09:15,803
Billy Cusimano.
- Organic grocery guy?

128
00:09:16,380 --> 00:09:20,188
It didn't come from me.
- No, just a well-placed, extremely attractive government source.

129
00:09:22,384 --> 00:09:25,285
Cusimano

130
00:09:31,181 --> 00:09:34,957
Hey Dad! Here?
- Yeah.

131
00:09:37,358 --> 00:09:38,607
Hello!

132
00:09:45,957 --> 00:09:47,494
Billy Cusimano?

133
00:09:47,782 --> 00:09:50,597
My name's Ben Shepard,
from the Albany Sun-Times,

134
00:09:50,887 --> 00:09:53,124
I wanted to ask you a few questions
about the Sharon Solarz arrest?

135
00:09:53,894 --> 00:09:58,094
You can, but why would I comment about that?
- Well, you know her, don't you?

136
00:09:58,671 --> 00:09:59,908
No, I don't.

137
00:10:01,971 --> 00:10:05,892
Quick search of police records shows you
and Sharon together in Mendocino in 1971.

138
00:10:06,083 --> 00:10:07,223
I've never been to Mendocino.

139
00:10:07,896 --> 00:10:11,299
That's not true, is it? You were dealing hash there
for an outfit called the Brotherhood of Eternal Love.

140
00:10:11,492 --> 00:10:13,709
Which is a great name, by the way.

141
00:10:14,284 --> 00:10:15,812
Sharon been in touch recently?

142
00:10:16,985 --> 00:10:19,700
Look, I know she called
you prior to her arrest.

143
00:10:20,181 --> 00:10:23,096
You talked to Jim Grant.
- No, I talked to the FBI, who's Jim Grant?

144
00:10:23,289 --> 00:10:25,964
Who is the FBI?
- Well, they had you on a wiretap here for a while,

145
00:10:26,061 --> 00:10:28,792
so it seems you're growin' somethin' more
than tomatoes and potatoes here, Billy.

146
00:10:28,889 --> 00:10:33,888
Shit. That's why I pay taxes, right?
So Big Brother can... hack my fuckin' phone!

147
00:10:33,985 --> 00:10:36,291
Who's Jim Grant?
- He's a lawyer, man.

148
00:10:36,386 --> 00:10:39,562
Lawyer? Sharon's?
- Nah, he wouldn't take the case.

149
00:10:39,563 --> 00:10:40,523
Look, kid...

150
00:10:40,707 --> 00:10:43,403
Sharon called me wanting to turn herself in...
- Turn herself in?

151
00:10:43,499 --> 00:10:46,793
Nope, I'm not saying anything else.
Everything here is off the record.

152
00:10:46,890 --> 00:10:50,103
Ah, see... it doesn't work that way. You gotta say
"off the record" before we have the conversation.

153
00:10:50,199 --> 00:10:52,295
Who says?
- Those are the rules.

154
00:10:52,392 --> 00:10:54,511
There's rules for what you people do, huh?

155
00:11:16,478 --> 00:11:20,006
So, what did she say?
- She said that I did great

156
00:11:20,102 --> 00:11:22,221
and that she was very impressed.

157
00:11:24,081 --> 00:11:25,343
What'd I tell you?

158
00:11:31,178 --> 00:11:34,059
Yeah?
- Hi... uh, is this Mr. Grant?

159
00:11:34,156 --> 00:11:37,862
This is Ben Shepherd from the Albany Sun-Times?
- Oh... yes.

160
00:11:37,958 --> 00:11:40,147
<i>Just wondering if you care to comment
on the Sharon Solarz arrest?</i>

161
00:11:41,396 --> 00:11:43,919
- What?
- The Sharon Solarz arrest, you declined to take her case...

162
00:11:44,111 --> 00:11:48,200
Yeah, you know... I'm just sitting down to dinner right now.
I gotta call you back, okay?

163
00:11:48,297 --> 00:11:49,448
Uh, sir... I ju...

164
00:11:57,788 --> 00:11:59,888
As the turbulent decade drew to a close

165
00:11:59,985 --> 00:12:02,387
the Students for a Democratic Society,

166
00:12:02,484 --> 00:12:04,916
the leading student group
opposed to the war in Vietnam,

167
00:12:05,013 --> 00:12:10,313
had its power usurped by a more militant faction,
known as the Weather Underground Organization.

168
00:12:10,696 --> 00:12:12,996
Frustrated with years
of non-violent protests

169
00:12:13,093 --> 00:12:14,898
that had failed to end the war,

170
00:12:14,995 --> 00:12:19,178
the so-called "Weathermen" decided the best
way to stop America's involvement in Vietnam

171
00:12:19,465 --> 00:12:21,197
was to bring the war home.

172
00:12:21,294 --> 00:12:23,922
The Weathermen radicalized the anti-war movement,

173
00:12:24,019 --> 00:12:27,476
and carried out a series of bombings
against government institutions including

174
00:12:27,572 --> 00:12:31,102
bombing the Pentagon, the U.S. Capitol,
and the State Department.

175
00:12:31,392 --> 00:12:35,227
No group has been more successful
in carrying out attacks on U.S. soil.

176
00:12:44,509 --> 00:12:46,908
What's wrong?
- Nothin'.

177
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:50,021
You look weird.
- I'm fine, honey.

178
00:12:51,013 --> 00:12:54,112
You're lying.
- I'm not lying...

179
00:12:54,306 --> 00:12:57,204
You are lying, because you're smiling.

180
00:12:57,205 --> 00:13:01,102
I'm not smiling.
- "I'm not smiling."

181
00:13:01,202 --> 00:13:05,974
Well maybe I'm happy?
Here. Come on, eat.

182
00:13:06,481 --> 00:13:08,510
And then get ready.

183
00:13:14,782 --> 00:13:16,415
Hey!
- Hey.

184
00:13:16,703 --> 00:13:20,011
- You Jim Grant, by chance?
- Not by chance.

185
00:13:20,608 --> 00:13:23,447
Would you follow up on those
counter-signatures from Roger?

186
00:13:23,448 --> 00:13:24,504
Yep.

187
00:13:24,900 --> 00:13:28,107
I'm Ben Shepherd, Albany Sun-Times, we spoke on the phone.
I just figured I'd come by and say hi...

188
00:13:28,204 --> 00:13:31,827
I don't really have anything to say...
Oh, and Susan, would you pull out the Rochester files for...?

189
00:13:31,925 --> 00:13:34,808
You don't know what I'm gonna ask you yet.
- ..the report for my deposition? Do what?

190
00:13:34,905 --> 00:13:36,832
I said you don't know what I'm gonna ask you yet.

191
00:13:37,697 --> 00:13:39,113
Well, you're a reporter.

192
00:13:39,306 --> 00:13:41,417
Well, I could just put "Refused
to answer any questions."

193
00:13:41,609 --> 00:13:44,230
What?
- I'm just doing a little background, sir.

194
00:13:49,298 --> 00:13:53,578
Okay.
- Thank you! (Thank you.)

195
00:14:01,990 --> 00:14:04,419
No, no... we're off the record here.

196
00:14:04,611 --> 00:14:06,806
Which part?
- All of it...

197
00:14:06,906 --> 00:14:10,610
whatever it is we're gonna be talking about here,
otherwise, you can leave now.

198
00:14:10,803 --> 00:14:12,520
No, that's fine.
It's not important.

199
00:14:16,292 --> 00:14:19,319
So, did Sharon Solarz contact you
prior to her arrest?

200
00:14:19,896 --> 00:14:23,105
Does it matter?
Since you already printed that she did?

201
00:14:23,205 --> 00:14:26,904
Actually, what was printed was that she may have approached
a public-interest lawyer who declined to take the case.

202
00:14:27,001 --> 00:14:28,549
But your name was never mentioned.

203
00:14:33,801 --> 00:14:35,729
There are 25 lawyers in the area.

204
00:14:35,826 --> 00:14:38,617
Nine do criminal,
six do accidents,

205
00:14:38,713 --> 00:14:41,317
five do deeds, and four do closings...
and then there's me.

206
00:14:41,414 --> 00:14:43,530
I wasn't insinuating...
- The hell with accuracy, huh?

207
00:14:44,107 --> 00:14:47,626
Be vague, be accusatory, and whatever sticks? Is that how it works?
- Nothing I wrote was false.

208
00:14:47,723 --> 00:14:50,174
You made it seem like I was
harboring a known fugitive.

209
00:14:51,902 --> 00:14:55,919
We can issue a correction.
- Sharon Solarz... did not contact me,

210
00:14:56,122 --> 00:14:58,510
and I have no involvement in her case.

211
00:14:58,607 --> 00:15:00,046
Really?
- Really.

212
00:15:01,007 --> 00:15:04,012
Do you know she's now being represented
by a Margaret Hart in Philadelphia?

213
00:15:04,108 --> 00:15:07,447
Right.
- Ms. Hart was a classmate of yours in law school?

214
00:15:07,448 --> 00:15:08,407
Mm-hmm.

215
00:15:08,696 --> 00:15:10,308
Lawyers know each other,
that's news?

216
00:15:10,405 --> 00:15:12,835
Yeah, but you did refer Ms. Hart
as counsel, didn't you?

217
00:15:13,412 --> 00:15:15,845
Says who?
- Ms. Hart herself, this morning.

218
00:15:16,229 --> 00:15:19,029
Maggie Hart is one of the best
defense lawyers in the country.

219
00:15:19,125 --> 00:15:21,816
But why pass this off? I mean,
that's what doesn't make sense to me.

220
00:15:21,913 --> 00:15:24,316
Cases like this don't come around very often,
I'm sure I don't have to tell you that.

221
00:15:24,414 --> 00:15:27,121
'Cause Sharon Solarz deserves a
better defense than I can provide.

222
00:15:27,218 --> 00:15:29,513
Deserves? That's
an interesting word choice.

223
00:15:29,898 --> 00:15:33,625
You know, it may seem untrue to you,
but we do live in a free country

224
00:15:33,722 --> 00:15:36,021
and people are entitled to
a decent defense.

225
00:15:36,214 --> 00:15:37,922
Now look, I got work to do.

226
00:15:38,403 --> 00:15:40,222
You've handled First Amendment cases,

227
00:15:40,319 --> 00:15:42,116
labor cases, you worked
hand-in-glove with the ACLU...

228
00:15:42,117 --> 00:15:43,914
I mean, this is right in
